          "id": "supply-chain-management-401-l01-c1",
          "title": "Types of Supply Chain Risk",
          "content": "In the fascinating world of supply chains, there are various types of risks that can impact how products are created and delivered to customers. Let's take a closer look at these important categories of risks: (1) Operational risks refer to challenges that arise during the production process. This can include situations where equipment unexpectedly breaks down, issues with the quality of products, or not having enough resources to meet customer demand. (2) Supply risks occur when a supplier goes out of business, when a company relies too heavily on just one supplier, or when there are shortages of essential raw materials needed for manufacturing. (3) Demand risks happen when businesses miscalculate how much of a product will be needed, or when there are sudden changes in demand, either a spike or a drop. This can create a ripple effect known as the bullwhip effect, where small changes in demand can lead to larger fluctuations throughout the supply chain. (4) Environmental risks involve unexpected events such as natural disasters, pandemics, or climate-related incidents that can disrupt the flow of goods. (5) Geopolitical risks are associated with international matters, including trade wars, government sanctions, or changes in regulations that can significantly affect supply chains. (6) Cyber risks involve threats to digital systems, such as data breaches or ransomware attacks that can disrupt logistics operations. Understanding these different types of risks is essential for businesses to effectively manage and prepare for potential challenges in their supply chains.\nContext recap: In the fascinating world of supply chains, there are various types of risks that can impact how products are created and delivered to customers. Let's take a closer look at these important categories of risks: (1) Operational risks refer to challenges that arise during the production process. This can include situations where equipment unexpectedly breaks down, issues with the quality of products, or not having enough resources to meet customer demand. (2) Supply risks occur when a supplier goes out of business, when a company relies too heavily on just one supplier, or when there are shortages of essential raw materials needed for manufacturing.\nWhy this matters: Types of Supply Chain Risk helps learners in Business connect ideas from Digital Supply Chains & Resilience to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
