          "id": "supply-chain-management-401-l02-c1",
          "title": "What Is Supply Chain Resilience?",
          "content": "Supply chain resilience is a crucial concept in business that describes how well a company can handle unexpected challenges while continuing to operate smoothly. This means being able to foresee potential problems, prepare for them, react effectively when they happen, and bounce back quickly afterward. There are two main parts to understanding supply chain resilience: resistance and recovery. Resistance refers to the strength of a supply chain in enduring disruptions without suffering major setbacks. For example, if a natural disaster strikes, a resilient supply chain can still function with minimal interruptions. On the other hand, recovery is about how swiftly a company can return to its normal operations after a disruption. This is vital because the faster a company can recover, the less impact it will face on its overall performance. It's also important to recognize that a supply chain that is highly resilient might not always be the most efficient one. Investing in resilience can sometimes mean spending resources on capabilities that seem excessive during regular times. However, these investments can be incredibly valuable during crises when unexpected challenges arise, ensuring that the company can continue to serve its customers and maintain its operations effectively.\nContext recap: Supply chain resilience is a crucial concept in business that describes how well a company can handle unexpected challenges while continuing to operate smoothly. This means being able to foresee potential problems, prepare for them, react effectively when they happen, and bounce back quickly afterward. There are two main parts to understanding supply chain resilience: resistance and recovery. Resistance refers to the strength of a supply chain in enduring disruptions without suffering major setbacks.\nWhy this matters: What Is Supply Chain Resilience? helps learners in Business connect ideas from Digital Supply Chains & Resilience to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
