          "content": "Traditional demand forecasting methods often depend on looking back at past sales data and using statistical models that are typically updated every month or quarter. This means that businesses might not have the most current information when making decisions about what products to stock. On the other hand, demand sensing is a cutting-edge approach that leverages machine learning technology to analyze real-time data signals. This can include various types of information such as point-of-sale data, which shows what customers are buying right now, website traffic that indicates how many people are visiting online stores, trends from social media that reflect what products are popular, weather forecasts that can affect buying behavior, promotional calendars that highlight upcoming sales, and economic indicators that provide insights into overall market conditions. By utilizing demand sensing, companies can create short-term forecasts that are updated on a daily or even hourly basis. This agility allows businesses to respond quickly to changes in demand. Companies that implement demand sensing techniques have reported impressive results, including a reduction in forecasting errors by 30-40%. This improvement not only helps in better inventory management but also leads to lower levels of safety stock and fewer occurrences of stockouts, ensuring that customers can find the products they want when they need them.\nContext recap: Traditional demand forecasting methods often depend on looking back at past sales data and using statistical models that are typically updated every month or quarter. This means that businesses might not have the most current information when making decisions about what products to stock. On the other hand, demand sensing is a cutting-edge approach that leverages machine learning technology to analyze real-time data signals. This can include various types of information such as point-of-sale data, which shows what customers are buying right now, website traffic that indicates how many people are visiting online stores, trends from social media that reflect what products are popular, weather forecasts that can affect buying behavior, promotional calendars that highlight upcoming sales, and economic indicators that provide insights into overall market conditions."
